If you write a proper Forth for your computer in assembly language it should be pretty much as fast as hand tuned assembly language because that's more or less what it is. The core dictionary is probably written in assembly language anyway. You could write words in Forth and if you hit a bottleneck replace a word with an assembly language version of it for more speed as you go.

This is why a "real" Forth is superior to the types which are written in C and compiled.

Chat bots are everywhere these days, most people wouldn't believe it but my guess is that at least half of all forum posts and news item and youtube comments and social media posts are fake, maybe up to 90% fake.
